  // -- FAQ --
  faq: [
    { question: 'What types of furniture worksheets can I create?', answer: 'You can generate a wide variety of furniture-themed worksheets including room layout design activities, preposition practice with furniture scenes, shape identification within furniture items, size comparison and ordering tasks, matching furniture to rooms, shadow matching with furniture silhouettes, coloring pages of room interiors, word searches with furniture vocabulary, pattern recognition with furniture arrangements, and odd-one-out puzzles identifying which item does not fit.' },
    { question: 'Are the furniture worksheets free to use?', answer: 'Yes, LessonCraftStudio lets you create and download furniture-themed worksheets at no cost. Choose your preferred worksheet type, select the furniture theme, customize settings like difficulty and number of items, and generate a printable PDF ready for your classroom or home learning session.' },
    { question: 'What age groups are furniture worksheets suitable for?', answer: 'Furniture worksheets are designed for children ages 3 through 9, covering preschool through third grade. Younger children work with simple matching, basic prepositions, and coloring, while older students tackle room layout design, multi-step word problems, complex spatial descriptions, and classification with written explanations.' },
    { question: 'How do furniture worksheets teach spatial reasoning?', answer: 'Furniture arrangement is fundamentally a spatial task, requiring children to think about positions, orientations, and relationships between objects in space. Preposition worksheets develop spatial vocabulary, room layout activities build spatial planning, and shadow matching develops spatial memory. These combined skills form the foundation for geometry, measurement, and mathematical visualization.' },
    { question: 'How do furniture worksheets connect to geometry?', answer: 'Every piece of furniture is built from geometric shapes: rectangular table tops, circular clocks, cylindrical legs, square drawers, and triangular shelf brackets. Worksheets that ask children to find, trace, and name these shapes show that geometry describes the real world, making abstract shape concepts concrete, memorable, and immediately verifiable by looking at any furniture item nearby.' },
    { question: 'Can furniture worksheets teach about room organization?', answer: 'Yes, furniture worksheets naturally teach spatial organization by asking children to decide which furniture belongs in which room and how pieces should be arranged. This builds practical life skills alongside academic spatial reasoning, as children learn that thoughtful organization makes spaces more functional and comfortable.' },
    { question: 'What vocabulary do children learn from furniture worksheets?', answer: 'Children learn furniture names like bookshelf, wardrobe, nightstand, and armchair, spatial terms like above, beside, between, and in front of, shape vocabulary like rectangle, cylinder, and circle, and descriptive words like wooden, cushioned, tall, and wide. This rich vocabulary supports both academic reading and everyday communication.' },
    { question: 'How do furniture worksheets differ from household worksheets?', answer: 'Furniture worksheets focus specifically on the design, shapes, and spatial arrangement of individual furniture pieces, emphasizing geometry, size comparison, and spatial vocabulary. Household worksheets take a broader view of the entire home, covering room identification, daily routines, safety concepts, and object classification across all aspects of domestic life.' },
    { question: 'Are furniture worksheets good for visual learners?', answer: 'Furniture worksheets are excellent for visual learners because they rely heavily on spatial visualization, shape recognition, and visual arrangement skills. Room layout design, shadow matching, grid matching, and pattern recognition all engage visual processing, making furniture one of the strongest themes for children who learn best through spatial and visual experiences.' },
    { question: 'How often should children complete furniture worksheets?', answer: 'Two to three sessions per week works well for building spatial reasoning and geometry awareness. Each session should last ten to twenty minutes depending on age. Because furniture concepts are continuously reinforced by the child\'s physical environment, even brief worksheet sessions produce lasting spatial learning gains when paired with occasional conversations about real furniture arrangement and design.' },
  ],

